Summary of this dataset:¶

The dataset includes the places serving food such as grocery stores, bakeries, restaurants and school cafeterias across Chicago city. These establishments pass, fail or have certain conditions related with passing the inspection. The dataset also indicates the risk levels and exact locations of the food stations with violation records. The original source is the City of Chicago Data Portal.

Data type:¶

Inspection ID, License #, Zip, Latitude, Longitude - numeric DBA Name, AKA Name, Facility Type, Risk, Address, City, State, Inspection Type, Results, Violations - string Inspection Date - datetime

My Visualization¶

The the intentions and goals of the project:¶

As the data analysts of U.S. Food and Drug Administration (FDA), in order to improve the pertinency and efficiency of FDA inspection of Chicago area in year 2020, we make an analysis of city food stations based on historical risk levels, business type (license ID), inspection results and violation records.

Issue:¶

People frequently report food security problems of Chicago food stations to FDA.

Demonstrate issue:¶

I will calculate the violation frequencies of different merchants, showing the line chart of repeating business types of offenders (by license ID) with merchants as x axes and frequencies as y axes. I will also categorize different violation types, displaying the histograms on frequencies of appearance of each type with violation types as x axes and frequencies as y axes.

Description of program:¶

We will conduct abrupt inspection of high-risk-centralized area, investigating the food stations according to risk levels from high to low. FDA will have a second focused inspection on specific merchants that had most violation records after all inspections. And I will compare the most frequently happened violation types of 2020 with that of 2019. This campaign aims at reducing the neglected food security issues of 2019 in the coming year and discover the changing trend of violation types.

Demonstrate success of program:¶

I will visualize a map on distribution of different risk levels and inspection results of Chicago food stations. (etc. triangle = pass, circle = fail, red = risk 3, yellow = risk 2, grey = risk 1). The latitude and longitude can be modified to locate a certain area, which is convenient for analyzing the risk level of that area. I will also indicate the peaks of violation frequencies of different merchants and frequencies of appearance of each violation type. This will be helpful for FDA to inspect concentratedly on the merchant which has most violation records and the regulation which is violated by most merchants.

The things that did work and did not work:¶

I will only use Facility Type, Risk, Results, Violations, Latitude, and Longitude in the further visualization. This is because I will complete a map that shows the distribution of risk level and inspection results of food stations.

Steps to generate this main visualization for my primrary dataset:¶

First, I dropped the empty values of latitude and longitude in the dataset since the location cannot be NaNs in the map visualization. Then, I selected the fist 1000 values in the dataset to have a test in visualizing the map. After that, I had a simple visualization of the locations the test data to provide an overview of my visualization. Next, I generate a base map with the location of Chicago city as the center. Finally, I add marks of the test data (1000 values) in the map. This visualization give people an overview of all the locations of the food station in Chicago area, and this prepare for my following visualization that includes the distribution of risk level of sanitary inspection conditions. This interactive map which allows shrinkage and enlargement helps people to find specific location of the food stations.

Contextual Data:¶

The following are three contextal data visualization that provide more information in analzing the sanitary condition of Chicago food stations. The first one describes the pass and fail numbers of all inspections. The second one is three risk level numbers of all inspections. The third one is inspection number by zip code. This three visualizations can help us to better understand the overall inspection result of the Chicago food stations. And inspection by zip code will provide more detail for us to refine visualization in the map.
